Implants vs. Bridges

Bone requires stimulation to stay dense. Bridges sit on top of gums, causing atrophy. Implants stimulate bone like natural roots.

Recovery Dashboard

Monitor your healing with our clinical indicator guide.

Normal

First 48 Hours

Mild swelling and slight oozing are expected. Manage with cold packs and rest.

Caution

Bleeding > 24 Hrs

If active bleeding persists beyond day 1, bite on sterile gauze for 30 mins.

Critical

Numbness > 6 Hrs

Persistent numbness in lip or chin after anesthesia wears off requires evaluation.

Common Questions

Reviewed by Dr. Dhivakaran & Implantology Team

Is the procedure painful?
No. Implants are placed under local anesthesia, so you feel numb just like a filling. Most patients report less discomfort than a tooth extraction. Post-op soreness is managed easily with standard painkillers for 1-2 days.
How long do they last?
With proper hygiene (brushing/flossing), dental implants can last a lifetime. The titanium screw is permanent. The crown may need replacement after 15-20 years due to normal wear, similar to natural enamel.
Can I get implants if I have diabetes?
Yes, provided your diabetes is controlled (HbA1c ≤ 7.5%). We use specialized implant surfaces (like Straumann SLActive) that accelerate healing specifically for diabetic patients. Uncontrolled diabetes poses a higher failure risk.
How long is the healing period?
Typically 3-4 months for the bone to fuse with the implant. In some cases with excellent bone quality, we can load the crown immediately.
What if I don't have enough bone?
We can perform bone grafting or a sinus lift to build up the bone volume before or during implant placement to ensure a stable foundation.
